Welcome to Future Histories, my name is Jan Gross, and it is my great pleasure to welcome Pat Devine in today's episode.

00:08.000 --> 00:16.000
With his 1988 book Democracy and Economic Planning, The Political Economy of a Self-Governing Society,

00:16.000 --> 00:23.000
Pat Devine put forward a concrete formal model of how democratic economic planning could actually work,

00:23.000 --> 00:29.000
and it is one of the essential reads for people interested in the debate, I would say.

00:29.000 --> 00:41.000
Since then, he has contributed to the topic in multiple publications, amongst others he was the guest editor of the 2002 special issue of Science and Society,

00:41.000 --> 00:48.000
and as regular listeners will know, these special issues are part of the Envisioning Socialism project,

00:48.000 --> 00:54.000
which is concerned with pushing forward the debate around democratic economic planning,

00:54.000 --> 01:05.000
and these special issues, they are released every 10 years, and I already mentioned he was guest editor in 2002, and we now have 2022,

01:05.000 --> 01:11.000
so this year has been one of those years where a new special issue came out,

01:11.000 --> 01:23.000
and I used this as an opportunity to record a small mini-series of interviews with central authors involved in this science and society project called Envisioning Socialism.

01:23.000 --> 01:33.000
The episodes with Robin Hannell on Paracon and with David Leibman on Multilevel Democratic Iterative Coordination have been released already,

01:33.000 --> 01:40.000
and the release of today's episode with Pat Devine concludes this mini-series within future histories,

01:40.000 --> 01:50.000
even though, of course, the planning debate in a broader sense will stay with us, since this is one of the main strands of future histories, so to speak.

01:51.000 --> 02:00.000
Before we start, I would like to thank Wilfried, Lucas, Karl, Fabian, Benedict and Marie for their kind donations,

02:00.000 --> 02:07.000
and I want to point you all to the English episodes only RSS feed and home page,

02:07.000 --> 02:18.000
so if you are an English speaker, you can simply subscribe to the English episodes of future histories now through the RSS feed or visit the home page, of course.

02:18.000 --> 02:22.000
futurehistories-international.com

02:22.000 --> 02:32.000
So please subscribe and tell all of your friends, and now please enjoy today's episode with Pat Devine on Negotiated Coordination.

02:37.000 --> 02:38.000
Welcome, Pat.

02:38.000 --> 02:40.000
Thank you very much.

02:40.000 --> 02:45.000
Let's start with a definition. What is democratic planning?

02:45.000 --> 02:52.000
Well, I came to the idea of democratic planning, we'll probably come partly to this later on as well,

02:52.000 --> 03:01.000
through thinking about the fact that Soviet-style top-down planning proved not to work,

03:01.000 --> 03:12.000
and the principal alternative that certainly people who continued to believe that some sort of socialist economy was necessary

03:12.000 --> 03:19.000
turned out to be market socialism, and I wasn't happy with market socialism,

03:19.000 --> 03:27.000
because it seemed to me that particularly from Marx's work, The Critique of the Goethe Programme,

03:27.000 --> 03:34.000
there were sort of two fundamental features of a post-capitalist society.

03:35.000 --> 03:44.000
One was the end of exploitation. Well, market socialist enterprises, you could argue, were able to deal with that.

03:44.000 --> 03:48.000
But the other was the end of the anarchy of production.

03:48.000 --> 03:59.000
And the anarchy of production, in effect, is the same thing as Adam Smith's invisible hand, or what today is called market forces.

04:00.000 --> 04:06.000
And since market socialism, although it changed the character of the enterprise,

04:06.000 --> 04:15.000
and therefore you could say abolished or potentially abolished exploitation, it didn't deal with the anarchy of production.

04:15.000 --> 04:27.000
And so what happened was that autonomous enterprises, state-owned or worker cooperatives or whatever, competed against one another.

04:27.000 --> 04:29.000
That's what market forces are about.

04:29.000 --> 04:40.000
And that was intended to be a way of ensuring that there was incentive structures for enterprises

04:40.000 --> 04:46.000
to make sure that they were producing efficiently and what consumers, users wanted.

04:46.000 --> 04:56.000
But that seemed to me to violate the second essential feature of Marx's view of socialism.

04:56.000 --> 04:59.000
And so I thought, well, what are the alternatives?

04:59.000 --> 05:14.000
And the alternative seemed to be not to rely on competition as a mechanism, but rather to rely upon cooperation, discussion, negotiation.

05:14.000 --> 05:25.000
And that's why I developed this idea of a layered structure of decision making and implementation

05:25.000 --> 05:36.000
based on the principle of subsidiarity, which originally comes from, believe it or not, the Catholic Church, the concept of subsidiarity,

05:36.000 --> 05:51.000
where decisions, at least in principle, are to be taken and implemented at the most local level that is consistent with all people affected by the decisions

05:51.000 --> 05:55.000
being involved in making them and carrying them out.

05:55.000 --> 06:13.000
So that essentially is what led me to look at the history of working class and popular involvement, struggles and demands to be involved in decision making,

06:13.000 --> 06:18.000
not just political decision making, but also decision making with respect to the economy.

06:18.000 --> 06:22.000
And there are historical examples of that.

06:22.000 --> 06:30.000
But what really led me in this direction was the fact that in the 1970s, which you of course won't remember,

06:30.000 --> 06:46.000
but the 1970s was, if you like, a crucial turning point for the capitalist world because it was the decade in which inflation got completely out of control.

06:46.000 --> 06:56.000
So in the UK, in the middle of 1975, the rate of inflation had reached 50 percent per annum.

06:56.000 --> 07:00.000
Now, that for a developed capitalist country is very high.

07:00.000 --> 07:05.000
And it was clear that something had to be done about it.

07:05.000 --> 07:21.000
And there were two approaches to it, one which the Polish economy, Michael Kulecki, had predicted in the 1940s during the Second World War,

07:21.000 --> 07:35.000
which was, well, the idea that unemployment is a problem for capitalism, which is, of course, what socially involved people thought unemployment is a bad thing.

07:35.000 --> 07:44.000
But Kulecki argued that the fact of the matter is the smooth functioning of capitalism depends on unemployment.

07:44.000 --> 07:47.000
It's a structural feature of capitalism.

07:47.000 --> 07:53.000
And therefore, if you were going to, as happened at the end of the Second World War,

07:53.000 --> 08:01.000
if you were going to follow the work and the expectations that had been done during the war,

08:01.000 --> 08:12.000
summed up for the UK in the report of beverage, full employment in a free society, where a free society was, of course, a free capitalist society,

08:13.000 --> 08:16.000
then how would it work?

08:16.000 --> 08:28.000
And the problem with full employment for capitalism, as Kulecki saw it, was that it meant that the working class was stronger

08:28.000 --> 08:36.000
in full employment situation, both in terms of the negotiations to get a job.

08:36.000 --> 08:46.000
But secondly, also, when you had a job and you were working in an enterprise and you wanted to have some play in how it was done, how it was being run.

08:46.000 --> 08:57.000
So Kulecki predicted that if we had full employment, it would cause problems, as indeed it did in the 1970s,

08:57.000 --> 09:05.000
when full employment resulted in this decade, really, of mounting inflation.

09:05.000 --> 09:10.000
And there were basically two ways of dealing with that.

09:10.000 --> 09:15.000
One was not that it was put this way, but in fact, it's what happened.

09:15.000 --> 09:25.000
One was to recreate unemployment, which is what happened with the advent of neoliberalism, Thatcher, Reagan, and so on.

09:25.000 --> 09:39.000
But the other was to do a deal with the unions and to say, look, if we get money wage increases at a higher rate than the increase in the rate of productivity,

09:39.000 --> 09:44.000
then that's going to result in price increases.

09:44.000 --> 09:50.000
Because if you've got an oligopolistic situation, as you had in all the developed capitalist countries,

09:50.000 --> 09:58.000
an enterprise could increase prices without altering its competitive position with respect to other enterprises,

09:58.000 --> 10:06.000
because the oligopolistic situation was one in which they had to take account of one another's actions.

10:06.000 --> 10:13.000
And so if one enterprise increased prices, the others would do the same without altering their relative positions.

10:13.000 --> 10:23.000
So the proposal that was put forward in the UK was to have a prices and incomes policy,

10:23.000 --> 10:41.000
whereby the unions representing Labour, the capitalist organisations and the government would come together to agree on what age increases would be,

10:41.000 --> 10:47.000
what price increases they would be, and that would solve the problem.

10:47.000 --> 10:55.000
Now, at that time, I was on the Economic Advisory Committee of the Communist Party in the UK,

10:55.000 --> 11:02.000
and we were in a minority there saying, look, this is a crisis, something's got to be done about it.

11:02.000 --> 11:13.000
What should happen, we think, is that the unions and the Labour Party and the Communist Party should support the prices and incomes policy,

11:13.000 --> 11:24.000
but on condition. And the conditions were, well, since real income increases would depend on the increase in productivity on the one hand

11:24.000 --> 11:35.000
and the distribution of output between profits and wages on the other hand, prices and incomes policies have to be policies in which it's agreed

11:35.000 --> 11:43.000
that trade unions can be involved in the decisions that affect the rate of productivity increase.

11:43.000 --> 11:52.000
And that meant basically impinging on managerial prerogatives, the prerogatives of capital.

11:52.000 --> 11:57.000
They're the ones who decide on investment, on new technology and so on.

11:57.000 --> 12:02.000
Unions had to be involved in taking those decisions as one of the conditions.

12:02.000 --> 12:09.000
The other was there had to be an agreement on the share between wages and profits.

12:09.000 --> 12:17.000
And that meant that unions, when I say unions, I'm talking of the representatives of the workers, obviously,

12:17.000 --> 12:25.000
would have to agree on whether the distribution between wages and profits was what they were prepared to accept.

12:25.000 --> 12:36.000
Now, that actually would have involved a move towards increasing social control over the decisions to do with economic matters

12:36.000 --> 12:41.000
and increasing the input of workers in those decisions.

12:41.000 --> 12:55.000
And we saw that as a step towards eventually getting rid of the capitalist element by moving towards taking over ownership, social ownership of the enterprises.

12:55.000 --> 13:00.000
So that you can see is the beginnings of negotiation and agreement and coordination.

13:00.000 --> 13:07.000
And that, in a sense, was the beginnings of my thoughts on how one would move to what we didn't want.

13:07.000 --> 13:11.000
We didn't want a top down plan system.

13:11.000 --> 13:18.000
We had that to some extent in the nationalised industries, but they were rather paternalistic.

13:18.000 --> 13:26.000
And they didn't involve workers or, for that matter, consumers and users in the decisions with respect to the industry.

13:26.000 --> 13:36.000
What happened was that they were made by people who thought they were doing the right thing for people rather than people doing things for themselves.

13:36.000 --> 13:38.000
So that's the origin of it.

13:38.000 --> 13:49.000
And that's why it had to be a structured layer combining, if you like, centralised decisions where the issues at stake affected everybody.

13:50.000 --> 14:00.000
And then more localised decisions where the decisions involved only affected, well, in the case of, say, the running of an enterprise, the workers in that enterprise.

14:00.000 --> 14:08.000
So they would operate with an enterprise in which the overall criteria were set more generally.

14:08.000 --> 14:16.000
But how to operate and implement within the enterprise those criteria was up to the people working in the enterprise and doing it.

14:16.000 --> 14:21.000
So that's why it needed to be a structured layer of decision making.

14:21.000 --> 14:36.000
And it meant that workers, instead of being passive recipients of decisions that other people had made, were in fact themselves involved as agents in making the decisions.

14:36.000 --> 14:55.000
So it was also, we thought anyway, a way in which you could move towards within still a capitalist system towards overcoming the various forms of alienation that are created by the operation of capitalism.

14:55.000 --> 15:00.000
So that is basically what the model is about.

15:00.000 --> 15:15.000
It's about enabling people at different levels in relation to different decisions and in different ways to be involved in those decisions so that they feel some sort of responsibility for them.

15:15.000 --> 15:33.000
At the same time as making sure that they are decisions that they feel are in their interests, but not only in their interests, but in the interests of other people who will also be affected by the decision, which is why they too have to be involved in the process of making decisions.

15:33.000 --> 15:43.000
So that's a long winded way of saying, well, I see the underlying sort of focus of democratic planning is based upon participation.

15:43.000 --> 15:50.000
That's very nice to see that this is actually coming from a very practical involvement that you had with actual politics.

15:50.000 --> 15:51.000
Yes, absolutely.

15:51.000 --> 15:57.000
And then you tried to form a model around these experiences, actually.

15:57.000 --> 15:59.000
That's very interesting.

15:59.000 --> 16:12.000
I could just add that during that period of the prices and incomes policy, there was also drawn up initially, funnily enough, by a conservative government.

16:12.000 --> 16:15.000
But then they lost power or lost the election.

16:15.000 --> 16:24.000
And so there was then a Labour government and they formed there was a national plan was drawn up in the UK.

16:24.000 --> 16:41.000
This national plan was a response to the fact that with the end of colonialism, with the end of imperialism, well, maybe not the end, but the weakening of it, that privileged position that it gave the UK economy was undermined.

16:41.000 --> 16:51.000
And so the UK economy is losing way to other economies with all capitalist economies, but it was becoming relatively weaker.

16:51.000 --> 16:55.000
And that process, of course, has gone on and on and on ever since.

16:55.000 --> 17:05.000
But so that meant that something had to be done, as it were, productivity increases were small, et cetera, et cetera.

17:05.000 --> 17:21.000
And so a national plan was drawn up and the national plan again was drawn up by discussion between the government, the unions and the employers representatives.

17:21.000 --> 17:27.000
And they agreed on plans to improve the performance of the economy.

17:27.000 --> 17:39.000
And then underneath that, that was called the National Economic Development Council, National Economic Development Council, which came to be known as a NEDE for some reason or other.

17:39.000 --> 17:45.000
And underneath that, there were little NEDEs, which were comparable bodies for each industry.

17:45.000 --> 18:00.000
So each industry would have a little NEDE where the trade unions representing workers in that industry, the government or the local government and the employers organizations at that level would again come together

18:00.000 --> 18:08.000
and see how they would best implement the provisions of the overall plan within their particular industry.

18:08.000 --> 18:14.000
So that was another, if you like, example of a layered process of decision making.

18:14.000 --> 18:17.000
The national plan failed, but that's another matter.

18:17.000 --> 18:22.000
So we are already very deep in the subject matter.

18:22.000 --> 18:33.000
I think maybe to kind of also introduce the audience to the topic, let's approach the thing on a more abstract level.

18:33.000 --> 18:46.000
I mean, you very nicely elaborated how you came to your specific model of negotiated coordination, but maybe just as a very short description, an abstract description,

18:46.000 --> 18:57.000
what are the main characteristics of a democratic planned economy in general compared to other types of political economy?

18:57.000 --> 19:12.000
Well, I suppose at the most general level, it means that the society, whether it's a local society or a regional society or a national society

19:12.000 --> 19:27.000
or a international society or a global society, all these different levels, they all get together to decide at the appropriate level

19:27.000 --> 19:40.000
what the policies that would contribute to human well-being, the best policies to contribute to human well-being would be as they currently saw things.

19:40.000 --> 19:47.000
And then they would discuss again at the different levels how to implement that.

19:47.000 --> 19:56.000
So, for example, take the issue of climate change at the moment, which is obviously a very hot issue, probably the most important issue.

19:56.000 --> 20:06.000
So it's quite clear what needs to be done at a global level, but it's not at all clear that it's going to be done.

20:06.000 --> 20:16.000
And that is because of the conflicting interests of the different countries and within the different countries, the different sectors of public opinion,

20:16.000 --> 20:19.000
the different sectors of the economy and so on.

20:19.000 --> 20:32.000
So what this would do would be to say, OK, at that level, global level, there would be agreement reached upon what needed to be done

20:32.000 --> 20:41.000
in order to deal with the climate change, the loss of biodiversity, global warming and all the rest of it.

20:41.000 --> 20:50.000
And then there would have to be agreement on how what needed to be done would be distributed between the different countries.

20:50.000 --> 20:55.000
And that would obviously have to depend upon the historical record.

20:55.000 --> 21:07.000
That is to say, the developed capitalist countries are the ones most responsible for the climate crisis and the loss of biodiversity, not the only ones, but the main ones.

21:07.000 --> 21:16.000
And that would obviously have to be reflected in the decisions about how much of what needed to be done had to be done by the different countries.

21:16.000 --> 21:27.000
And a similar process would apply within each country and then within each country, within each region and then within each region, locality.

21:27.000 --> 21:40.000
So it would give people directly and indirectly control over what needed to be done in order to contribute best to human flourishing,

21:40.000 --> 21:50.000
taking into account the different positions that different parts of the globe, different sections of the community are in,

21:50.000 --> 21:59.000
different responsibilities, how you were going to agree on what would be a reasonably fair way of dealing with this.

21:59.000 --> 22:11.000
And the point that one has to realize is that this is not sounds implausible in our existing society because that's not how capitalism works.

22:11.000 --> 22:23.000
But if you're in a socialist society, some people thought of a socialist society as a society in which there would be no difference of views.

22:23.000 --> 22:32.000
That's why the government or even the party or even the political committee could take decisions which would affect everybody.

22:32.000 --> 22:35.000
But that's not how life is and it can never be.

22:35.000 --> 22:54.000
And so it's a way of enabling people at different levels to feel that they or their people like them or groups that represent them are involved in a real way in making the decisions

22:54.000 --> 23:10.000
and carrying them out to their and everybody else's in that particular group of people to their benefit, taking account of the fact that if what they do affects other people in a significant way,

23:10.000 --> 23:22.000
then they too have to be involved in taking the decision. So it's if you like participation, it's not sort of passive democracy, it's active participatory democracy.

23:22.000 --> 23:33.000
Now, there is a problem. We've come across this because a close colleague of mine, an ex PhD student of mine, Fitred Adaman from Turkey, of whom I've written a lot.

23:33.000 --> 23:42.000
We've written a lot together, but he has been quite influential within Turkey in promoting this idea of participation.

23:42.000 --> 23:54.000
And there have been various studies carried out trying to bring together parties in particular areas, different interests to see if they can arrive at some sort of agreement.

23:54.000 --> 24:06.000
And very often they do arrive at an agreement, but then nothing happens because they don't have the power to ensure that what's agreed is then actually carried out.

24:06.000 --> 24:18.000
And so we've decided that there's a danger in certain circumstances, just like there's a danger of greenwash where, you know, oil companies say they're doing something.

24:18.000 --> 24:31.000
But there's also a danger we've decided of participation wash. People feel that they're actually participating, but they're not really participating in a way that makes a real difference to what happens.

24:31.000 --> 24:42.000
And that's, if you like, why you can't talk about all the things, the ideas that we've been working on as relevant within a capitalist society.

24:42.000 --> 24:55.000
You have to think of ways in which those ideas can be used to promote prefigurative actions of one sort or another that would lead further in the direction.

24:55.000 --> 25:02.000
And, you know, there are plenty of examples around of people who've thought similarly.

25:02.000 --> 25:09.000
I mean, the other another person I've spent quite a lot of time studying and working on is Karl Polanyi.

25:09.000 --> 25:14.000
And he has this idea of the double movement.

25:14.000 --> 25:22.000
Capitalism causes problems. Society strikes back and regulates that causes capitalism to seize up.

25:22.000 --> 25:28.000
So you get, if you like, the opposite movement to reestablish the market.

25:28.000 --> 25:41.000
And it goes on and on like that until society in the end takes full control over its economic aspects, which means you have to, in his terminology,

25:41.000 --> 25:48.000
get rid of the fictitious commodities market for capital, labor and money.

25:48.000 --> 25:58.000
So you can move in those directions within capitalism in a prefigurative way or in ways that then lead to the next stage of demands.

25:58.000 --> 26:09.000
But you can't really expect to be able to implement things in the way that the model envisages unless you get rid of capitalism.

26:09.000 --> 26:24.000
And one of the ways in which you can help to do that is by this idea of moving in that direction through various forms of prefiguration and theoretical and ideological work and so on.

26:24.000 --> 26:38.000
Brilliant. I absolutely share this analysis 100%, specifically the idea that we need prefigurative politics and actions in the here and now.

26:38.000 --> 26:47.000
But we do also need formal models of how a democratic participatory plant economy could actually look like.

26:47.000 --> 26:53.000
So let's dive a little deeper into how your model is set up.

26:53.000 --> 27:00.000
Could you describe the core elements of your model, which you call negotiated coordination?

27:00.000 --> 27:15.000
Well, OK, so the first building block is the concept of what I call social ownership, not private ownership, not state ownership, but social ownership.

27:15.000 --> 27:28.000
And social ownership, I think of as ownership of all the groups that are going to be affected by the use of the assets involved.

27:28.000 --> 27:40.000
So if you've got an activity which only affects a small local area, then it could be run by an individual or a small co-op or whatever.

27:40.000 --> 27:55.000
If you've got an enterprise which covers a wider area, then it would need to be owned by the interests within that wider area who are affected.

27:55.000 --> 28:04.000
And so it comes back to what I was saying about the climate change, the environmental ecological crisis we're facing.

28:04.000 --> 28:13.000
There'll be different levels at which decisions have to be taken because different people are affected at different levels.

28:13.000 --> 28:21.000
At each of those levels, the people who are the groups that are affected need to be the social owners.

28:21.000 --> 28:31.000
So that's the concept of social ownership, ownership by the groups of people who are affected by the decisions, by the use of the assets involved.

28:31.000 --> 28:39.000
And so that then leads me because I'm now thinking more in terms of economic activity.

28:39.000 --> 28:44.000
I mean, you can apply the same principles more generally to political and social activity,

28:44.000 --> 28:52.000
but I'm thinking more generally because after all, I've come at it from the standpoint of an economist or a political economist, I like to think.

28:52.000 --> 29:03.000
So then you say to yourself, OK, if you take an industry at the level of the enterprises that constitute that industry or sector of the economy,

29:03.000 --> 29:16.000
whatever you want to call it, the people who are going to be affected by the activities of that enterprise are the people who work in it.

29:16.000 --> 29:27.000
People who use what it produces, either consumers or other enterprises, if they're intermediate goods that the enterprise produces,

29:27.000 --> 29:32.000
the locality in which the enterprise is based and the people who live there.

29:32.000 --> 29:46.000
So just let's take those three, those three groups, workers in the enterprise, users of what the enterprise produces and the locality where the enterprise is based.

29:46.000 --> 29:52.000
They would be the social owners in a simplified way of the enterprise.

29:52.000 --> 29:59.000
You might also want to say, well, we might want still to have people who are greens,

29:59.000 --> 30:07.000
who are concerned about the way the enterprise will affect the environment and the ecology, and that's the focus of their interest.

30:07.000 --> 30:16.000
Similarly, you might want to have groups or associations of people who are concerned with equal opportunities,

30:16.000 --> 30:28.000
who would also if you decided that enterprise was such that it needed those things or more, they would be part of the group of social owners as well.

30:28.000 --> 30:37.000
And they would be responsible for the activities of the enterprise using its existing productive capacity.

30:37.000 --> 30:44.000
And they would then produce with that productive capacity what they thought was needed.

30:44.000 --> 30:56.000
And that would be a way of generating information because if consumers or other enterprises didn't want to make use of what they were producing,

30:56.000 --> 31:07.000
that would be evident in the fact that they would produce more than they could sell or they would have to lower their prices and then they wouldn't be able to produce as much and so on.

31:08.000 --> 31:11.000
So that would be at the level of the enterprise.

31:11.000 --> 31:26.000
But then if the size of the industry needed to increase or to shrink, either because increase because demand for it, what it produced was increasing and so on,

31:26.000 --> 31:37.000
it would have to either invest or disinvest, and that would affect all the people who were the social owners of the enterprise.

31:37.000 --> 31:47.000
But since there'd be more than typically more than one enterprise in an industry or a sector, other enterprises would be faced with the same problems.

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
Were they going to expand or shrink?

31:50.000 --> 32:01.000
And therefore, when it comes to a process of how do you decide on the pattern of investment across all the enterprises in the industry or sector,

32:01.000 --> 32:06.000
that doesn't only affect one enterprise, it affects all of them.

32:06.000 --> 32:15.000
And therefore, they all have to be involved as the social owners of the decisions about investment, major investment in the industry.

32:15.000 --> 32:21.000
And therefore, what would happen is that you would have a negotiated coordinating body.

32:21.000 --> 32:34.000
So they would get together and they would have the information about the performance of individual enterprises, how that what they were producing was being received by the users.

32:34.000 --> 32:44.000
But they would also have information about the work situation in the area where the enterprises were based.

32:44.000 --> 32:54.000
There might be some areas which were suitable only for this type of enterprise and other areas which were suitable for all sorts of different enterprises,

32:54.000 --> 33:08.000
in which case you'd think, well, the area that was only suitable or the activity that was only suitable for this area is probably the one where activity should expand,

33:08.000 --> 33:13.000
investment should be so that there's work for people in that area to do.

33:13.000 --> 33:18.000
Areas where you can easily move from one type of production activity to another,

33:19.000 --> 33:26.000
maybe don't need the same amount of activity from this industry, they can have activity from others.

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
So you'd have to take that into account as well.

33:29.000 --> 33:45.000
And you'd arrive then at a decision about the allocation of investment or disinvestment if the industry was shrinking across the body of enterprises that constituted the industry.

33:45.000 --> 33:54.000
And if the industry was expanding, you might even need to take account of other areas where the industry wasn't currently based.

33:54.000 --> 33:59.000
But maybe there was a shortage of work there or activity there.

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
And this particular activity was suitable there.

34:02.000 --> 34:12.000
So you would be able to establish new enterprises in such areas rather than expand existing enterprises.

34:12.000 --> 34:31.000
So where you've got interdependent decisions that would affect people in this wider group of areas or this wider group of enterprises that would have to be taken by negotiation between all the affected groups.

34:31.000 --> 34:34.000
So that would be the second sort of strand of it.

34:35.000 --> 34:49.000
And that, I noticed in one of your questions, that for me is the distinction between market exchange, which is what the individual enterprise engages in.

34:49.000 --> 35:01.000
And in capitalism, how the interdependent activities of the different enterprises are coordinated is through the operation of market forces.

35:01.000 --> 35:08.000
Profitable enterprises expand, unprofitable enterprises contract or disappear.

35:08.000 --> 35:15.000
But that happens in ways that nobody really has any control over.

35:15.000 --> 35:22.000
It just happens because if you're making a profit, you can expand and if you're not, you can't and you have to contract.

35:22.000 --> 35:28.000
So market forces produce outcomes that no one willed.

35:28.000 --> 35:29.000
Nobody planned them.

35:29.000 --> 35:32.000
They just happen as a result of the operation of market forces.

35:32.000 --> 35:39.000
Negotiated coordination is an alternative to market forces as a way of coordinating activity.

35:39.000 --> 35:53.000
It's also less wasteful because the problem, as, for example, the English economist Morris Dobb emphasized, is that where you've got interdependent decisions to be made,

35:54.000 --> 36:01.000
which the outcome of one depends upon what other people are doing as well as what you do.

36:01.000 --> 36:16.000
It's better if you can to coordinate those decisions in advance rather than let them be coordinated after the event by the operation of market forces.

36:16.000 --> 36:29.000
Now, that also brings us to one of the other questions or points you've made in your list of questions, which would be helpful, which was the two different sorts of certainty.

36:29.000 --> 36:40.000
So Morris Dobb emphasized that within a economy which is coordinated through the results of market forces operating,

36:40.000 --> 36:50.000
one form of uncertainty is created by the fact that you don't know what other enterprises are going to be doing,

36:50.000 --> 36:56.000
whereas what other enterprises are going to be doing will affect the outcome of what you're doing.

36:56.000 --> 37:10.000
So that's one sort of uncertainty. That can be abolished by planning, ex ante planning, planning in advance rather than ex post coordination after the event.

37:10.000 --> 37:24.000
Now, the second sort of uncertainty is uncertainty of the sort that Keynes was referred to when he was trying to draw a distinction between uncertainty and risk.

37:24.000 --> 37:36.000
That if you know what the possible outcomes are and what the probability of those outcomes is going to be or is, then you can calculate the risk.

37:36.000 --> 37:46.000
But what about things where there's an outcome that nobody knows? But it could happen. You don't even know what it is.

37:47.000 --> 37:57.000
So this is what he was talking, of course, within a capitalist economy. So he said nobody knows what the price of copper is going to be in 20 years time.

37:57.000 --> 38:07.000
So you can't really plan that. It's not quite true. You could plan it anyway. That's a different area we could go into.

38:07.000 --> 38:23.000
So what we call ex ante coordination, coordination before the implementation of these decisions, even though the outcome of each decision depends also on what the other decisions are.

38:24.000 --> 38:38.000
Coordination ex ante can get rid of the first sort of uncertainty, but not, of course, the second sort. And for that, then you need contingency planning and all the rest of it.

38:38.000 --> 38:59.000
But so really, what this would enable would be society at different levels within that people who comprise the societies, having some sort of control over the direction of development of economic activity.

38:59.000 --> 39:10.000
What sort of new investment would be needed? What sorts of new industries would be needed? Because you also have planning boards at different levels.

39:10.000 --> 39:25.000
And it would also mean that people weren't subject to things beyond their control, like, you know, nowadays, a factory decides to be the owners of a factory decide to close it without any consultation of the workers.

39:25.000 --> 39:32.000
Or maybe they have to negotiate with the workers to avoid a strike or whatever it is. And it may destroy the area.

39:32.000 --> 39:53.000
I mean, when the coal mines shut in the UK, whole areas, whole towns and villages, which depended upon the coal mines for their lives, it's structured the whole sort of social, cultural, political activities of the life of the people who live there.

39:54.000 --> 40:11.000
Suddenly all went. And of course, nothing was replaced, replacing it. The idea would be, you know, the Neo, the market forces idea is that, well, if this activity goes, it means that there'll be unemployment, wages will be down.

40:11.000 --> 40:20.000
So new forms of capital will come in. And that it'll all work out in the long run. But it's all very well to talk about the long run. But what about the people who live there in the short run?

40:20.000 --> 40:40.000
So there we are. I mean, that's, I suppose, basically what I would see the advantage of a participatory planning model based upon social ownership and negotiated coordination.

40:41.000 --> 40:55.000
I think it would be great because you already started to sketch the institutional framework that you lay out within your book. And you started by describing social ownership, what you think this should be like.

40:56.000 --> 41:20.000
You describe the production units, at least in a rough form, and then went on to describe that there will be negotiated coordination bodies, which will coordinate, for example, sectors, depending on the level, so to speak, that needs to be addressed in a given industry, depending on the reach of how many people in which areas are affected by it.

41:20.000 --> 41:31.000
But maybe it would be good to try to complete the picture of the institutional setup, because you briefly touched upon the fact that there will be planning commissions.

41:31.000 --> 41:47.000
But within your model, there is indeed a very kind of concrete idea of how this whole process would actually work out and which bodies, institutional bodies are involved in it.

41:47.000 --> 42:07.000
And I think it would be great for the listeners to get an idea of the whole process of production units transferring economic information and meeting within negotiated coordination bodies, which will then transfer the accumulated information, so to speak, to a planning commission.

42:07.000 --> 42:11.000
They will develop a plan and so on and so on.

42:11.000 --> 42:20.000
I think it would be great to kind of sketch the rough picture of the whole process of functioning of the model, so to speak.

42:20.000 --> 42:31.000
Yes, well, I suppose, I mean, the way I see it is that you've got this layered structure of decision making and implementation.

42:31.000 --> 42:50.000
And each level of the structure operates within a framework that has been set by decisions of the higher levels of decision making bodies in the structure, the more general levels, put it that way.

42:50.000 --> 43:03.000
So, for example, if we're talking about a socialist or communist society, we would be talking about a society in which there was no unearned income.

43:03.000 --> 43:13.000
There would be income for people who couldn't contribute, couldn't work or who were ill or who were young or who were old, of course.

43:13.000 --> 43:30.000
But people who are perfectly capable of working wouldn't obtain income by virtue of owning capital or land or whatever you might think about it.

43:30.000 --> 43:45.000
So you'd have a set of values in which production for use rather than production for profit would be the value that people had internalized.

43:45.000 --> 43:54.000
And you'd also have ideas of social human well-being, human flourishing and what was needed for that.

43:54.000 --> 43:58.000
And so there would be certain basic needs that had to be met.

43:58.000 --> 44:04.000
And there would be also, one would expect, plenty of time.

44:04.000 --> 44:09.000
You could call it free time, if you like, or time where you weren't actually working.

44:09.000 --> 44:14.000
But you might be doing other sorts of things that could count as work if you wanted to think about them like that way.

44:14.000 --> 44:20.000
You know, time for recreation, for creativity, for artistic activities.

44:20.000 --> 44:30.000
You'd also have a system in which the different sorts of work, particularly in this country at the moment, there's a big discussion going on about caring work.

44:30.000 --> 44:41.000
And at the moment, people who do caring work, whether within the family or the household or whether through paid caring work,

44:41.000 --> 44:50.000
it's usually seen as rather sort of low level work, certainly lowly paid compared to all sorts of other things.

44:50.000 --> 44:57.000
So you'd have a different set of values. Such activities would be valued much more highly than they are in capitalist society.

44:57.000 --> 45:04.000
Unless, of course, if you're a very rich capitalist society, you can employ servants and all the rest of it.

45:05.000 --> 45:11.000
So I suppose at the most general level, you'd have political discussions.

45:11.000 --> 45:18.000
That's why the subtitle of my book was called The Political Economy of a Self-Governing Society.

45:18.000 --> 45:28.000
And this self-governing society is not a state that governs, hands things down, but is a self-governing society in a layered structure.

45:28.000 --> 45:38.000
And so you'd have, for example, at the highest level, the most general level, you'd obviously have to have legislation to do with, say,

45:38.000 --> 45:47.000
human rights, equal treatment, people not being able to be discriminated against and so on.

45:47.000 --> 45:55.000
And that would create a framework within which at lower levels, you'd have to take account of that.

45:55.000 --> 46:05.000
So you couldn't have a situation where, say, a local village or government council decided they didn't want any Roma or Gypsy people.

46:05.000 --> 46:13.000
That would not be allowed as a result of the higher level framework that would be established at that level.

46:13.000 --> 46:24.000
And so that's the sort of principle that would apply about the relationship between the different levels politically, but also economically in terms of economic activity.

46:24.000 --> 46:32.000
And so you'd have a political structure, which again would be a layered structure.

46:32.000 --> 46:49.000
There'd be an overall probably world, if not government, then at least a world set of institutions which would decide on, as we've already said, on policies to do with climate change, biodiversity and so on.

46:49.000 --> 47:03.000
And then they could have regions like the EU, which unfortunately the UK has left, but it could have stayed in and tried to change the things about it that it didn't like in discussion with other people.

47:03.000 --> 47:11.000
People who voted to leave are now discovering that what they expected would be great and turned out to be a problem.

47:12.000 --> 47:19.000
We don't need to go there. So I think you'd have a layered political structure.

47:19.000 --> 47:40.000
You'd have a layered economic structure which would include what you could call planning boards to do with a local area, a city, a region, a country, a set of regions like the EU or the world.

47:40.000 --> 48:06.000
I mean, at the moment, for example, it does seem ridiculous that we have most of the goods that used to be produced in the developed capitalist countries before deindustrialization are now produced in China or similar less developed countries

48:06.000 --> 48:16.000
and then shipped all the way back, as it were. The technology often comes from the West, but the goods are produced and then shipped for the West to use.

48:16.000 --> 48:26.000
So when it comes to CO2 emissions, you can't only take account of these CO2 emissions in producing what you produce in your own country.

48:26.000 --> 48:34.000
You have to take account of the CO2 emissions that are produced by other countries on your behalf that are then exported to you.

48:34.000 --> 48:42.000
So I would expect that, of course, people concerned would have to decide at the time when we got there.

48:42.000 --> 49:05.000
But I would expect there'd be a move to much more, if you like, local, localized production, which would be then spread more fairly across the world and within a country, across the country, taking account of geographical, climatic, et cetera, conditions.

49:05.000 --> 49:12.000
And I would expect, therefore, there to be much less, if you like, transportation across the world.

49:12.000 --> 49:17.000
But who knows? I mean, that might be wrong, but that's what I would expect.

49:17.000 --> 49:37.000
But that wouldn't be decided, obviously, by me. That would be decided by the people in a participatory democratic fashion, layered fashion, deciding at the different levels what was best for the people who lived there, for them, and so on.

49:37.000 --> 49:59.000
So you could argue that the level of the negotiated coordination body, there would not only be, it would not only consist of the enterprises in the industry or sector, the places, the regions where those enterprises were based, other regions that perhaps

49:59.000 --> 50:08.000
were under provided for in terms of economic activity and the planning board that would put that input into it.

50:08.000 --> 50:24.000
So you'd have a structure, in a way, not too different from what was planned, say, in the national plan in this country, except it was a national plan that existed on paper only.

50:24.000 --> 50:31.000
It didn't exist in reality. If you like, at best, within the terminology, you could call it indicative planning.

50:31.000 --> 50:45.000
But indicative planning, which has been tried in various capitalist countries, never works, because for it to work, all the people who've got to follow the indications in the different parts of the economy don't necessarily all do it.

50:45.000 --> 50:59.000
So it begins to, that's why the national plan fell apart, because it envisaged that there would be a certain balance between imports and exports, and there wasn't.

50:59.000 --> 51:09.000
And so it ran into a balance of payments crisis, which had effects on the value of the currency. And so the whole thing collapsed.

51:09.000 --> 51:16.000
So you've got to have a system in which decisions are made by the people who are going to be affected by them.

51:16.000 --> 51:23.000
And therefore, there's more chance of them actually being implemented because they've agreed on them.

51:23.000 --> 51:33.000
So it's not a society that I envisage or an economic activity structure that I envisage, which is all predetermined.

51:33.000 --> 51:40.000
It's activities decentralized, but within a centralized framework, if you like.

51:40.000 --> 51:54.000
So just to sum up, social ownership, negotiated coordinated bodies, planning boards, all operating in an interdependent way with the planning boards,

51:54.000 --> 52:10.000
if you like, representing the political side of things, the government or the authority structure at each level of the layered structure of decision making and implementation.

52:10.000 --> 52:16.000
I think that's probably the best I can do in terms of the institutional framework.

52:16.000 --> 52:31.000
I think we need to try to sketch maybe an example of how this would work out in concrete terms, because I mean, we now have this institutional framework.

52:31.000 --> 52:40.000
We have the production units, we have the negotiated coordination bodies, we have the planning commissions all on different levels.

52:40.000 --> 52:51.000
But how would the concrete planning and organization of economic production work out in concrete terms?

52:51.000 --> 53:05.000
There would be this flow of information, as we already touched upon from production units, and then this negotiation process at the level of the negotiation coordination bodies.

53:05.000 --> 53:15.000
And they would then transfer this, like then produce collectively produced information to the planning commission.

53:15.000 --> 53:23.000
But for example, at this point, maybe could you sketch an image of what this information would entail?

53:23.000 --> 53:31.000
Like what would be the level of precision in terms of information that would be transferred to the planning commission?

53:31.000 --> 53:36.000
And then so what are the information of inputs that lead into the planning commission?

53:36.000 --> 53:40.000
What are the processes within the planning commissions?

53:40.000 --> 53:44.000
You have to say in plural, because they are on many different levels.

53:44.000 --> 53:52.000
What are the processes within these planning commissions with which they try to develop a sensible plan?

53:52.000 --> 54:02.000
And what are the parameters along which this process tries to figure out what is seen as sensible and what is not?

54:02.000 --> 54:10.000
Because there are different elements to this, there are political elements to this, there are elements of like mere efficiency, so to speak.

54:10.000 --> 54:27.000
And so I would be interested in how this would go along in order to, at the end, produce a plan that is both sensible in terms of not wasting resources unnecessarily,

54:27.000 --> 54:43.000
and also able to lead to a consensus about the implementation of this given plan, because these are both like difficult goals to achieve, actually, I would say.

54:43.000 --> 54:58.000
Well, I suppose the first thing I'd say in response to that is that you talked about information flowing up through the different levels to inform what happens at each level.

54:58.000 --> 55:03.000
And that is undoubtedly one of the central processes that I would envisage.

55:03.000 --> 55:13.000
But equally, what you did mention, which I think is as important, is that there would also be information flowing down,

55:13.000 --> 55:26.000
so that the decisions that the enterprise makes are partly dependent on the framework set by the decisions made by the negotiated coordination bodies.

55:26.000 --> 55:34.000
And their decisions are likewise partially shaped by the information coming down from the Planning Commission.

55:34.000 --> 55:43.000
So there's, if you like, an interactive flow of information between the different levels, which is, one would hope,

55:43.000 --> 55:57.000
what would enable the different levels of decision making, the different bodies, to make the most effective use of the available, the relevant information coming from lots of different sources.

55:57.000 --> 56:12.000
So I've already said that one source of information would be the performance of the enterprise, each enterprise, in terms of what it's producing is received by its potential users.

56:12.000 --> 56:27.000
So you could have a situation in which the enterprise is producing more than its users want to use, whether they're consumers or other enterprises using intermediate goods.

56:27.000 --> 56:39.000
Equally, if that's the case, then what they do would be to either they'd have to build up stocks, inventories, the enterprises producing, they wouldn't be selling everything.

56:39.000 --> 56:52.000
Or if they weren't producing enough, then they would have order books, which weren't being fulfilled as rapidly as they would like to fill them.

56:52.000 --> 57:03.000
That would suggest that either the enterprise needs to expand or contract, depending upon whether it's producing too much or too little.

57:03.000 --> 57:30.000
But then that's one source of information that would be relevant to the negotiated coordination body, which would be interested in, if you like, the extent to which the resources organized within the enterprise were being used in a way that contributed to what people wanted.

57:30.000 --> 57:42.000
Then, of course, what people wanted, if we're talking about consumers, would be very different from what people want in a capitalist country where capitalism generates discontent.

57:42.000 --> 57:53.000
It's not just that you want more, but you always want different things because, you know, everything's rapidly made obsolete fashion changes, but the rest of it.

57:53.000 --> 57:57.000
So sort of turbo consumerism wouldn't exist.

57:57.000 --> 58:04.000
And what would you be interested in would be what contributes to human flourishing, human needs.

58:04.000 --> 58:18.000
And therefore, when you were considering how to say the level of the negotiated coordinating body, when you're considering what to do about the pattern of investment for the industry or sector that you're trying to work out,

58:18.000 --> 58:25.000
you'd have to take account on the one hand of how the individual enterprises were doing.

58:25.000 --> 58:42.000
On the other hand, you'd have to take account of what the situation within the localities in which enterprises were based, what the situation there was, was there the shortage of work, was there too much work, et cetera, et cetera.

58:42.000 --> 58:58.000
You'd also have to take account of information that the negotiating board coordination body got from the planning board, which was to say, well, at the political level, it's been decided that we need to prioritize.

58:58.000 --> 59:06.000
This form of development, we need to prioritize, for example, a shorter working week.

59:06.000 --> 59:11.000
So you'd have to take account of that in terms of how you were going to operate.

59:11.000 --> 59:22.000
Then in terms of what we've already talked about, climate change would affect the nature of the technology that you might have to move to or to install.

59:22.000 --> 59:44.000
So I don't know that one can do more, at least I can do more than just say, well, there'd be a lot of different sources of information coming from a lot of different groups who are likely to be differently affected by the decisions taken.

59:44.000 --> 01:00:05.000
And this information, because the groups themselves are participating in the discussions, is information which the groups themselves would be able to contribute to the discussion based upon their own experience, their own situation, which nobody else knows quite in the same way that they do.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:15.000
In other words, if I wanted to use technical terms, it would be able to draw upon the social tacit knowledge of the group.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:22.000
One of the things that the Austrians are always on about, or at least the modern Austrians, are tacit knowledge.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:32.000
It used to be distributed knowledge, but since Oscar Langer's model solved that problem, they've now fallen back on tacit knowledge.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:43.000
But when they think of tacit knowledge as individual knowledge, whereas, of course, you can have the tacit knowledge of a group learns how to work together and so on.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:50.000
So the tacit knowledge of the different interests, groups representing the different interests, would be contributed.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:01:10.000
And therefore, you'd have a situation in which there would be discussion about what to do, what decisions to make, based upon a consideration of all these different forms of knowledge that are relevant.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:30.000
And it would take place in a group of people whose psychological predisposition, whose values were, well, look, we're obviously concerned about how this is going to affect us, but we also are concerned about how it's going to affect other people.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:46.000
And therefore, we've got to come to an agreement about what the best outcome, not for everybody individually, but for the social owners as a whole would be.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:55.000
So it's an extension of John Donne's, no man is an island, no group is an individual group, and all it cares about is itself.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:01.000
It's part of a collectivity, and it's concerned with the well-being of the collectivity.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:07.000
And the collectivity includes people who are going to be differently affected by the decision.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:20.000
Some decisions will affect everybody adversely, but there's unlikely to be a decision that will affect everybody beneficially without if they didn't have to take account of other people.

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:25.000
So there'd have to be a process of discussion, negotiation.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:42.000
And, you know, in a way, again, from my own experience, I've had a very sort of minor, very minor indeed example of this in the university, which has a limited budget.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:46.000
Most universities don't have a large enough budget, but leave that aside.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:51.000
So you've got the different departments, the different faculties.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:54.000
They all want more resources.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:58.000
And they have a resource committee.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:12.000
And they have representatives from the different departments and faculties on this committee, and they argue and negotiate about how cuts or increases should be distributed.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:15.000
But in the end, they reach an agreement.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:21.000
Not everybody's happy with the agreement because they'd like more, but they'll live with it.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:25.000
And, of course, you could say, well, supposedly somebody says we won't live with it.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:35.000
Well, that's not how that's not the ethos of the sorts of discussion, sorts of negotiation that we're envisaging.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:41.000
If we're talking about a socialist or communist society, we're talking about a society.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:52.000
In which people's well-being depends as much on other people's well-being being catered for as on their own well-being catered for.

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.000
Solidarity, if you like.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
So obviously, you're right.

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:05.000
They have to be, you know, it might be democratic decision voting in a negotiated coordination body.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:06.000
There might be different ways.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:14.000
There might be sort of weighted votes for the different groups if it was decided that some groups were more effective than others.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:21.000
It might be with reserved levels of decisions, percentages of voting, depending upon.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:24.000
So a variety of different ways would be evolved.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:34.000
And I don't think in advance one can do more than sketch out these, at least I can do more than sketch out these general principles.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:42.000
And it would be a learning process through which people would learn about the interests of other people.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:54.000
It wouldn't be a process of preference aggregation because in the course of the discussions, the negotiations, people's preferences would change.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:05:01.000
So by participating in this process, you change yourself, not just other people.

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:07.000
I think there are some elephants in the room that need to be addressed.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:12.000
And I guess one of them would be the question of complexity.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:14.000
Complexity.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:15.000
Complexity, yes.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:26.000
I mean, in a very abstract and general sense, I absolutely understand where you're coming from and the idea of what you said in your last sentence,

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:37.000
that it is not only about a collection of existing preferences, but about a collective production of a shared interest, so to speak.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:43.000
And then the will and the ability to act upon it, maybe to add.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:45.000
I absolutely share this.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:53.000
But still, I mean, if we live in societies that have a degree of complexity that we do have right now,

01:05:53.000 --> 01:06:03.000
and I think there are absolutely great benefits to this kind of complexity as well as dangers, of course, but still.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:10.000
So it's not about getting back to a situation where everything is only produced on a local level,

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:19.000
where people kind of argue face to face how, what, and when things are being done.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:30.000
But we have a degree of complexity and that definitely needs different kinds of processes in order to bring about, for example,

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:41.000
also complex products. If you take a computer and then some production unit would have to address all of the different layers,

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:48.000
all of the different people, all of the different areas that are in one way or another affected by producing a computer,

01:06:48.000 --> 01:07:04.000
then this explodes the amount of people that would have to be involved in the decisions leading up to the final computer that we can use and work on.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:12.000
Because, I mean, we have rare minerals, we have all sorts of materials that are produced in different areas of the world, et cetera, et cetera.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:20.000
And about many of the ways in which these things could be produced, there will be conflict,

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:25.000
there will be different ideas of how things are being done, and so on and so on.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:33.000
So I guess the elephant in the room would then be if we have this principle of social ownership,

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:39.000
if we have this principle of everybody who is in one way or another being affected,

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:55.000
then you would immediately run into very concrete problems in terms of how to actually produce, for example, a complex product such as a computer.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:08:05.000
So maybe you could run us through the idea of how these questions could be addressed within your framework.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:15.000
Well, I think this is, if you like, a variation on Oscar Wilde's objection,

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:22.000
not objection, but witty comment on whether socialism would work, too many meetings.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:25.000
So I think it's a variation of that.

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:29.000
But the point is that, well, I'd make two points here.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:36.000
Well, three, actually, the idea that everybody would have to be involved in every decision,

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:46.000
because everybody in some sense, however remotely is affected by every decision, is not anything like what I envisage.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:57.000
I envisage, and I think the model envisages, that people are involved either directly or indirectly,

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:08.000
either face to face, as you put it, or via representatives in major decisions that affect them.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:15.000
So, for example, it could argue that within an enterprise,

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:22.000
if the workforce comes across a better way of doing things than had previously been the case,

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:28.000
and that required a bit of new equipment or something, which you could call investment.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:37.000
Minor investment like that would be within scope of the enterprise to do.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:47.000
If it came to major investment, like a whole new factory or workshop,

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:56.000
then that would have to be considered in terms of, well, does this count as something which would affect other people to some extent,

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:00.000
to such an extent that they need to be involved in the decision or not?

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:06.000
And you could only work that out, I think, really, as things evolve.

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:18.000
I mean, I could fall back upon the generally accepted view that Marx and Engels didn't say much about how a future socialist society would work,

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:25.000
because that would have to be worked out by the people who were doing it, who were there, who were implementing it.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:28.000
But in general, you can have the principles.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:39.000
And so I think my first sort of comment on that would be that it wouldn't be a situation where everybody had to be involved in everything,

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:51.000
even if everybody is thought of as everybody who might have at some level some small input into the decision at some time or other.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:55.000
So, I mean, at the moment, you talk about a computer.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:07.000
Well, now, the complexity of everything that goes into that, obviously true scientific endeavor, a lot of international cooperation,

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:14.000
maybe not as much as they should be, but because of private property rights and all the rest of it.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:22.000
Still, a lot of one of the problems that we're experiencing in the UK now, having left the EU,

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:30.000
is the extent to which we're still going to be involved in EU activities, scientific activities.

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:38.000
And surprise, surprise, they discover, well, if you're not in the EU, you don't actually have the same right to be involved as if you were in the EU.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:41.000
What a surprise. Anyway, that's something else.

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:49.000
So that's the first thing I'd say that these things happen at the moment without everybody feeling they have to be involved in everything.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:59.000
So that's the first thing. Second thing is at the moment in capitalist societies, you get a variety of institutional forms.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:09.000
So, for example, you get the multinational firm, which is has a headquarters somewhere that has branches.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:23.000
And there are different models. One model is not that similar to the distinction between market exchange and negotiated coordination over investment,

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:32.000
where the different branches of an enterprise submit their profits to a center and the center decides what to do with them,

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:38.000
how to allocate them to this branch or to close that branch or open another branch.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:43.000
So these sorts of things already happen to a significant extent.

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:58.000
And of course, if you've got a conflictual relationship like you do under capitalism, workers, even managers in one branch is being closed, might not be happy.

01:12:58.000 --> 01:13:07.000
But nevertheless, if they're not involved in the process of decision making, either directly or indirectly, what can they do?

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:16.000
There's not much they can do about it other than go on strike or work slow or and in the end that will probably cause the enterprise to shut.

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:30.000
The other thing to say, two other things to say, one is that actually, if you think about the way in which complex capitalist societies work,

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:38.000
they work almost exclusively based upon meetings.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:46.000
There are meetings of boards of directors. There are meetings of technical teams.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:57.000
There are meetings of human relations used to be called personnel. Now we're not personnel. We're not people anymore. We're just resources.

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:09.000
So one shouldn't underestimate the number of meetings that take place to run a complex capitalist society.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:37.000
One shouldn't also underestimate the extent to which a lot of those meetings are to do with how to deal with getting round regulations, capitalist rivalry, protecting intellectual property, fighting legal battles, all of which you'd expect would more or less disappear in a socialist, so communist society.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:50.000
So and then the third thing I'd like to say about that is that at the moment, we don't only have a functional division of labor, which you'll always need.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:15:02.000
That is to say, you have electrical engineers, mechanical engineers, etc. You have electricians, you have plumbers.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:14.000
So you have a functional division of labor. You also have accountants, managers, technicians.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:29.000
You also have doctors, lawyers, architects. So you've got a functional division of labor, but you've also got a social division of labor.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:49.000
That is to say, most people spend most of their time doing work of the same functional level, so skilled manual workers, professional workers, managers who run things, politicians.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:16:03.000
Most people spend most of their time doing those sorts of works. It's a bit like, you know, in the university, you don't only have academics, but you also have people who clean the rooms and the corridors.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:12.000
And most academics don't clean the rooms and the corridors. And most people who clean the offices and the floors aren't academics.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:36.000
So there are these different social divisions, and it's been found, I think it would be fair to say, that people who are the same social level of division of labor, even though functionally they're doing different things, find it much easier to talk to one another than they do to talk to people who are in a different social level.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:17:04.000
Now, if you, as I propose in my book, think of it that way, what I would envisage, what I argue for, is that we abolish the social division of labor, which is basically what Mark's talked about, the difference between intellectual and manual work generalized to the different social

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:22.000
division of labor. And we each, at various stages in our lives, or possibly at the same stage in our life, do different sorts of labor, which is currently now what is social division of labor divided.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:38.000
So, for example, you get this process of, in military terms, you had national service, where all young people, usually young men, had to join the national service.

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:55.000
There has been proposals, what some people call shit work, that is to say, you know, emptying dust bins, or sweeping streets, or digging ditches, or whatever it is, it's something that actually, you could have a sort of social service.

01:17:55.000 --> 01:18:06.000
And that could be done by, you know, young people, the necessary work that still remained after you went through as much mechanization and automation and so on as you can have.

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:18.000
And you could actually probably envisage, I mean, I did national service in the Royal Air Force in the UK, and although I wouldn't have had to spend my whole life doing it, it was quite an interesting experience.

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:28.000
And, you know, you learned something, it was boring, I wouldn't have wanted to spend most of my time doing it. But I was young, and you get through it.

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:43.000
And there's a certain camaraderie develops which you enjoy at that age and so on. But then, you know, I'm perfectly capable of cleaning my own office, but that's not how things are structured.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:19:00.000
So if we all did our fair share, give or take a bit of the different social levels of activity, social division of labor, rather than functional division of labor, we'd have experience of all these different levels.

01:19:00.000 --> 01:19:19.000
And it means, for example, that if we were involved, as for example, in the university, to some extent, where in the governing bodies of the university, people were mainly appointed, but there was a small proportion of elected members.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:42.000
And if you were elected, and you got involved in the decisions involved in running a university, you learned what was involved, what mattered. And then when you stopped being elected, because we were usually elected by the, because we were the sort of representatives of the union, who would put themselves forward for election and usually got elected.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:20:00.000
But you began to appreciate the problems that the management, if you like, was dealing with. And you didn't necessarily always agree with the decisions they made. But you could see that there were decisions that needed to be made, that weren't easy decisions.

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:25.000
And if you've had experience of that, it means that you approach it in a slightly different way. You're not always oppositional. And so no, we're not having that. You've got to think of something that what would you put forward as a way of dealing with the problem that would actually move things forward in the direction that you would like to see it go, rather than just no, no, no to everything.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:42.000
So it would mean that if you if you did that, there'd be less of a problem in terms of dealing with the complexity that you're talking about. And the fact that I think that this is just what I think, I have no idea whether this would be the case or not.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:21:00.000
That there'd be more, as it were, production would be more localized, not everything, of course, but more localized. So things that could be produced locally, probably would be produced locally, rather than being shipped across the world, because it could be produced slightly more cheaply

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:29.000
there, since you pay people less there, and so on, you'd get rid of all that. And I don't actually see complexity as a problem, really. It's, it's something that that obviously exists in modern society and will exist in all societies. But I don't see why it can't be dealt with by people having, as it were, been transformed by I mean, one argument that sometimes is, is, is, you know,

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:47.000
is used against participation as well. Maybe lots of people don't want to participate, or maybe they're not able to participate. But the point is that if you have never had the chance of participating running anything, then you probably don't want to get involved in it.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:22:06.000
Bit like participation wash. If what you do makes no difference, why bother? And so people learn by what they, by their life experience. And if they have life experience of different sorts, then they have a wider basis of experience to draw upon when thinking about things.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:16.000
Now, this probably doesn't dispose of your elephant, but I think it is, that's how I think about it anyway.

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:41.000
Well, it doesn't completely dissolve the problem, I'd say. So there's still some kind of elephant there, I'd say. And this is not because I wouldn't share like most of your arguments. I just think that, that they even taken together do not yet address, like the complexity of the problem itself.

01:22:41.000 --> 01:23:05.000
Because I mean, at the end, one like essential question would be how to draw the line. If you say that, okay, not everybody has to be involved in everything. And being like affected in a tiny bit by something does not really immediately lead to the necessity of you being involved in the process.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:33.000
Then, I mean, the immediately the question comes up, okay, but what is the parameter? What is the, what is the way in which this distinction is being made? Because if we stick to the example of a computer, then despite the fact that we do have a lot of meetings in capitalism as well, and all the arguments that you just gave, there's still at the end is the very concrete question that if the principle in general is that if you're involved in the process, then what is the parameter?

01:23:35.000 --> 01:24:04.000
If you're being affected by some of the elements that are involved in the production of a computer, then you will have to be involved within the process as such, then the problem still exists if we do not like have some kind of idea of how to define this threshold, so to speak, of how much being

01:24:04.000 --> 01:24:31.000
one necessarily being involved within a process or decision making process and stuff like that. And the question then is if there are like 30 different interests being represented within the board of a given production unit, then how to argue that the 31st should then not be included.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:50.000
I mean, there needs to be some kind of principle to draw a line of when something counts as being affected, because it's just a very like a question of principles as much as practice, you know?

01:24:50.000 --> 01:25:19.000
Well, I don't know. I don't really know what to say about that. I mean, at the moment, you've described the complexity of the inputs into making a computer. Okay, obviously, that's the case. Now, I suppose I would see that as a lower level decision than the decision as to whether or not one wants to have a computer made

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:46.000
in the first place. So there's been a lot of work done, less fashionable now than it used to be at some time, about the way in which technical progress, although it can't be predicted in advance the form it's going to take, but the direction in which it goes is shaped by the dominant interests in the society.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:26:08.000
So, for example, there's a lot of discussion now about social media or YouTube or whatever. Now, some people argue that these technologies are technologies that just develop almost independently, neutrally, they're just technologies that's there to be sort of discovered or created or whatever.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:37.000
Rather than the alternative view is that these technologies are developed in ways that suit or contribute to the existing ethos, the existing ways of things happening under capitalism. So I think at that level, there would be decisions about the direction in which one wanted technology to be developed.

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:52.000
Where did technology to go? Not the detail, because one can't predict that, but the direction in which one wants to go. Where does one want to put resources for future technological developments? Which teams of the sort that you're talking about?

01:26:52.000 --> 01:27:07.000
Does one want to support? And presumably, big companies do that all the time. They have to decide, are they going to favor this technique or that technique, or this direction of development or that direction of development?

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:23.000
Once that decision has been made, and the resources to finance it have been made available, then it's not up to the people who are making those decisions to actually implement it. It's up to the people who know about the structure.

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:40.000
So that's where, I mean, at a simple level, social owners would decide, just as the boards of directors do with private capitalist companies now, overall sort of priorities for the company or for the enterprise.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:51.000
But then it would be the people who work in the enterprise, who would be the ones who say, OK, this is what we need to be doing. This is what we need to be going. How are we going to do that?

01:27:51.000 --> 01:28:06.000
And then if they then come up with ideas for something new, they can put that. So you get two way flow of information. And that doesn't mean to say you wouldn't have specialist teams like the sort that you're talking about.

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:12.000
And of course, at one level, you know, if the butterfly stamps here, somebody dies across the other side of the world.

01:28:12.000 --> 01:28:25.000
But I mean, that sort of degree of involvement is not the sort of involvement that I have in mind, maybe wrongly when it comes to thinking about social ownership.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:45.000
I think of it as it were major categories of interests like consumers or workers. And when it comes to workers, I mean, I would and I do in my book say, well, of course, the main people who are going to be affected in implementing something are the

01:28:45.000 --> 01:29:01.000
workers in the enterprise concerned once the overall decisions by the social owners at the, if you like, board of directors or whatever level has reached their decisions.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:06.000
But then it's up to the workers in the enterprise to see how they can be best implemented.

01:29:06.000 --> 01:29:21.000
But in a sense, it's not just up to the workers in that enterprise, because the workers in the enterprise might say, well, you know, we want to make sure that this thing that we're working on is going to take off.

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:28.000
And therefore, we will cut wages by 20% so that it can be sold more cheaply.

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:43.000
Now, that would then have an effect on other workers. And therefore, as well as the workers in the enterprise itself, being represented as part of the social owners, you probably in a more minor way.

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:55.000
I'd say trade unions represented so that they could say, come on, you can't just cut workers that would be setting up wages, you can't be setting a precedent for everywhere else.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:30:09.000
We can't do that. And so they'd argue the case. So in other words, I always have found it difficult to go beyond the general principles, because I think that would have to be learned by doing.

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:19.000
Rather than pretty just prescribed in advance. I think the general principles, I'm fairly clear on and you seem to be happy with them too.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:26.000
How they actually work out in practice in detail.

01:30:26.000 --> 01:30:33.000
I can't I can't foretell that that would have to be worked out by the people who are doing it.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:46.000
Yeah, I guess my position would be that I think there are still some open questions in terms of the general principles as well, because they cannot that easily be separated from the practical implementation.

01:30:46.000 --> 01:30:54.000
That would be one point, I guess. And I mean, that's where, for example, modern information and communication technologies come into play.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:31:00.000
Or the question of formalizing a bit more how people would actually be involved.

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:17.000
What kind of decision making processes would be implemented in order to still provide this absolutely understandable benefit of having people that are affected by something being able to participate within the process, which I totally agree with.

01:31:17.000 --> 01:31:26.000
But still doing it in a way that kind of is aware of the practical implementation of the whole process as such.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:41.000
And I mean, one one thing that, as I said, immediately immediately pops up would be the question of how could like modern information and communication technologies maybe assist within this process?

01:31:41.000 --> 01:32:01.000
Because this in a world which is like highly diverse, highly interconnected and in which some processes of production are necessarily international and not local, this kind of needs to be addressed in some way, shape or form, I would say.

01:32:01.000 --> 01:32:07.000
And yeah, I mean, that's something I am absolutely interested in.

01:32:07.000 --> 01:32:29.000
The question of how could this maybe be technologically mediated in a meaningful way, not in a way which kind of eliminates the essential features of the thing, but assists with the handling of complexity when it comes to this.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:43.000
Yeah, you addressed it as too many meetings problem, and I do understand some of the arguments that you give against it, but still there is a rest of open questions when it comes to the question of complexity.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:33:00.000
And yeah, I'm asking myself how to, as I said, kind of maybe try to mediate it in a technological way that is really meaningful and not like stupidly deterministic, so to speak.

01:33:00.000 --> 01:33:07.000
Well, I think we probably have to leave this issue there because I can see.

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:16.000
Well, I mean, first of all, in terms of international, the fact that I envisage

01:33:16.000 --> 01:33:25.000
production being much more localized than it currently is doesn't mean to say I don't envisage there being some international exchange trade and so on.

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:28.000
So it's not complete autarky I'm talking about at all.

01:33:28.000 --> 01:33:46.000
And then the only other thing to say, which I've already said, is that within the sort of broad frameworks that are determined at a higher level, at a lower level, it's the people who are actually involved in doing it, who would have to work things out.

01:33:46.000 --> 01:34:04.000
And within that, I mean, I not myself had experience of that, but I imagine that if you decided to make a computer in this way, rather than that way, that would affect some people more than others, because some people have the skills for this way, but not for that way.

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:17.000
And, you know, it may be that people like you're talking about communication and so on, you know, that people have inputs into a process that they can put in from a distance.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:30.000
And so, I mean, all that seems to me to be the level of detailed implementation, rather than the overall framework and set of principles that one wants to apply.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:39.000
So, of course, in some sense, almost every decision anybody makes will have some impact on other people.

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:52.000
So it's a way of, as it were, on the one hand, deciding on the major minor groups that are going to be affected or individuals that are going to be affected at a lower level.

01:34:52.000 --> 01:35:18.000
And on the other hand, recognizing that I don't think we can predict in advance how these things are going to be resolved, other than to draw upon the undoubted sort of experience of technology under capitalism that happened as a result of people cooperating and skills and so on.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:31.000
But, you know, we could go back to Lenin, who I remember said that socialism can be built through Soviets on the one hand and electrification on the other.

01:35:31.000 --> 01:35:37.000
But he wasn't concerned about the details of the electrification.

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:44.000
He was just concerned about the fact that what it did was provide a source of energy that could then be used.

01:35:45.000 --> 01:35:47.000
So anyway, that's an aside.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:56.000
I mean, I hope it's all right if I have some pressing questions that we hopefully can cover, even though I already have taken up a lot of your time.

01:35:56.000 --> 01:35:58.000
No, no, it's absolutely fine.

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:20.000
Because, I mean, there are some very general questions concerning a model that I do have as well, because you kind of said, all right, the details, they will have to be produced, evolved, negotiated within the process, which I do understand, even though, as I said, I have some elephants.

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:27.000
Some of my elephants might be bigger than yours, but I have some general questions as well.

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:37.000
And one of those is addressing the kind of implicit anthropology, so to speak, that your model holds.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:42.000
I kind of labeled it Homo negotiatus and Homo activus.

01:36:42.000 --> 01:36:43.000
You did, yes.

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:58.000
Because, I mean, there is this specific idea, this specific image that your model relies on heavily, and that is the image of, and I quote you here, self-activating, self-determining individuals, end quote.

01:36:58.000 --> 01:37:04.000
And these self-activating, self-determining individuals should have control over their lives.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:18.000
And this image, it has a quite humanistic ring to it, I would say, and a strong belief into reason as the foundational and guiding principle of not only the political, but also the economic structures.

01:37:18.000 --> 01:37:29.000
And this is kind of, at least that was my impression, the point where the pluralism that you promote, the pluralism of your model actually collapses.

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:47.000
Because since the whole thing is based upon the idea of everybody being involved, everybody would have to somewhat commit to this ideal and not only commit to it, actually, but also incorporate it into the deepest levels of one's personality.

01:37:47.000 --> 01:38:05.000
And I was asking myself if there isn't some kind of essentialism at play here in which it is assumed that what everybody truly wants is to actively participate in all of this and to be this specific type of person.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:13.000
And during our interview, you already mentioned that there is, of course, this aspect of division of labor.

01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:32.000
And if this is overcome, then we would be able to learn different ways of approaching different kinds of skills, different kinds of labels, et cetera, and that this would also lead to a kind of development, also an internal development.

01:38:32.000 --> 01:38:59.000
And I do understand that point, and I think it's very valid, but I doubt that this addresses the underlying universalism within the assumption that given this development, at the end, everybody would want to participate and want to be this specific homo sapiens that you imagine as a basis for your model.

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:14.000
I mean, I think you put it in the question, something like the tension between interdependence and autonomy, and I just don't see that they are incompatible.

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:33.000
I think no man is an island, no person is an island, and we are shaped by our interaction with other people, by our social experience through our lives.

01:39:33.000 --> 01:39:46.000
And the idea that there is some essentialist characteristics of homo sapiens is it depends how you interpret that.

01:39:46.000 --> 01:40:08.000
I mean, my partner is a developmental psychologist and a linguist, and she has this very interesting issue associated with Chomsky, which on the one hand, he's got his sort of politics, broadly speaking, with which we agree.

01:40:08.000 --> 01:40:26.000
But on the other hand, in terms of language, his view apparently, and I'm no expert on this, his view apparently is that language is innately pre-wired.

01:40:26.000 --> 01:40:39.000
So it's part of the essential makeup of human beings, which is why all language, although it takes different forms, is basically the same and has the same structure.

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:51.000
And it's independent of the input. It's just there. And different inputs cause it to come out in different ways, but nevertheless, it's there.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:41:17.000
So this is a sort of innatist view of language. Now the other way of thinking about it, which is the one that my partner belongs to, is that, of course, nobody would deny that there is an innate capacity for human beings to learn language in a way that no other species has learned it.

01:41:17.000 --> 01:41:32.000
So that's not just by accident. It's because things have evolved to make that possible. So in that sense, language is innate, but the form it takes depends upon the input that people hear.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:53.000
And that shapes, and that's why you've got very, very different forms of language. And the debate between the two schools, of course, is between, you know, one school saying, well, yeah, yeah, but you can always interpret your findings of listening to how children learn to talk and so on in your way, but we can interpret it in our way.

01:41:53.000 --> 01:42:15.000
And that's how it goes. So I think that it's a sort of false opposition to talk about autonomy and interdependence as being incompatible. I think that whether we like it or not, we are all interdependent.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:32.000
And I actually do quite like it. I mean, I wouldn't like to be a hermit and be totally isolated, but that's neither here nor there. It's really that there are forms of interdependence, which are usually oppressive and alienating.

01:42:32.000 --> 01:42:58.000
And there are forms of interdependence, which are liberating and humanizing. And so I don't really see that it's a real problem, the way you've put it. If people haven't had the chance of interdependent activity in which they feel that what they're doing makes a difference, as I said before, they'll think, well, what's the point?

01:42:58.000 --> 01:43:20.000
And if they don't have to do it all their lives, because you don't have this social division of labor, so you can move from one thing to another. You can move from being as many people in our society do, being a professional to being a manager, and sometimes then to being a capitalist.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:44.000
But the other form of interdependence is interdependence of the working class movement, the labor movement, which is solidarity, support, cooperation. And I think those two forms, if you like, are learned through the experience you go through and the circumstances you find yourselves in.

01:43:44.000 --> 01:44:10.000
So I don't really think that is a problem, as I see it. I go back to Marx's distinction, again in the critique of the Goethe program, between what he calls the lower and the higher stages of communism, with the lower stage having come to be called socialism and the higher stage communism.

01:44:10.000 --> 01:44:35.000
But he talks about the lower and the higher stages of communism. And his point is that the lower stage of communism, i.e. after you get rid of capitalism, and you move to a socialist as opposed to a communist society, which he describes as from each according to ability.

01:44:35.000 --> 01:45:04.000
So you contribute what you can to each according to work. So you're rewarded in terms of how much you put in to the collective well-being. And that is because he thinks that at that stage, on the one hand, productivity hasn't reached the stage where there's enough to produce an equal amount for everything, for everybody.

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:28.000
Who needs it. So, but the other point about that is that when we move from capitalism to post capitalism, we are shaped by our experience of capitalism and all the prejudices, ways of thinking and so on and so forth that we take with us have been shaped by that form of society.

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:45.000
And so socialism or the lower stage of communism, as he puts it, is a process of, on the one hand, making sure that there's the ability to produce enough to satisfy needs.

01:45:45.000 --> 01:46:00.000
And on the other hand, the slogan is from each according to ability, we all do what we can, we put into the collective pot. But we get not what we put in the equivalent of what we put in, but what we need.

01:46:00.000 --> 01:46:27.000
So from each according to ability to each according to need and need then depends upon, well, what counts as what you need to contribute to human flourishing and much of what is consumed and people think they need under capitalism, probably most increasingly people would agree doesn't actually contribute to human flourishing.

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:44.000
So, you know, there's a problem of obesity. There's a problem of the sales where shops say there's one big prize that you can get, but half price, but there's only one.

01:46:44.000 --> 01:47:02.000
So people go up in advance, sometimes for days, in hope of getting this one prize and only one person can get it. And the thousands of others have been queuing up don't get it so they feel they've lost out, they discontented capitalism generates discontent.

01:47:02.000 --> 01:47:22.000
So you've got to, you've got to contribute to, you've got to think about what used to be perhaps it is called abundance enough to satisfy everybody's needs, not just in terms of how much can be produced, but also in terms of how much counts, or what counts as contributing to human

01:47:22.000 --> 01:47:41.000
wellbeing, what counts as needs. And so from that way, I think that some people may choose not to want to participate, but they've got to have the opportunity and the encouragement and the experience to enable them to do so if they'd like to.

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:55.000
And I don't see any reason why people wouldn't want to be involved in taking decisions that have major effects on their lives. But who knows? That's a learning process. I mean, we'll discover that by what happens.

01:47:56.000 --> 01:48:15.000
You touched upon many different things that I would like to follow up on. The first thing would be a clarification. I absolutely agree that the dichotomy of interdependence on the one hand and individual autonomy on the other hand, I do not share this as well.

01:48:15.000 --> 01:48:34.000
That was not the point that I was getting at with my question before. It was more addressed towards what you said at the end of your answer. And this kind of touches upon the question of compulsion to work as well.

01:48:34.000 --> 01:48:57.000
Because at the end, you said, okay, some people might not choose to participate. And this could mean participate in the process of democratically negotiating the goals of one's society or mode of production or whatever. But it might also include choosing not to work at all.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:23.000
And this is another question that I have concerning your model, because at some point within our talk today, you mentioned that there is no unearned income. And you directed it towards people who might profit from private capital. But there is also the question of whether there is or is not some form of universal basic income.

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:42.000
And I assume that this income will come additional to what I assume to be unconditional basic services that provide base amount of infrastructure for everybody, which I definitely see included in your thinking and the way you sketch your model.

01:49:42.000 --> 01:50:04.000
And with that, you seem to think that it is a necessary component of this type of model that people are kind of, quote unquote, forced to work through this trade-off of working and then receiving some kind of remuneration.

01:50:04.000 --> 01:50:28.000
Because this is kind of connected to the question that I had before when it comes to whether or not there is some idea of universal expectation towards the individuals to be this specific type of human.

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:48.000
Human, you know, this specific type of human that is self-reflective, active, engaged, participating and stuff like that. You know, this is kind of the ground material of your model and you build your institutions, the whole setup around this idea of how

01:50:48.000 --> 01:51:07.000
the individual human sees itself in relation to others, in relation to oneself and stuff like that. But I would argue, as you touched upon briefly in your last answer, that many people might function very differently.

01:51:07.000 --> 01:51:20.000
You know, they might not fit into this idea of active subject, active individual and stuff like that. And I would argue that there is a benefit in this as well.

01:51:20.000 --> 01:51:46.000
And that they, and this is like the long circle I'm kind of making, connecting these two questions. And I would argue this leads us into an area where there should not be some kind of first phase, second phase kind of distinction where in the first phase the work is connected to some kind of wage.

01:51:46.000 --> 01:52:02.000
And that you necessarily are, quote unquote, forced to work in order to get some kind of existence beyond basic, basic, basic needs. I'm not sure if this was understandable at all, the question.

01:52:02.000 --> 01:52:20.000
No, I mean, I think I would see that there would be a general expectation that people should contribute to the collective well-being of society, which includes themselves and other people.

01:52:20.000 --> 01:52:34.000
By taking part in economic activity, which creates the things that people need to flourish as human beings.

01:52:34.000 --> 01:52:51.000
And so I think that this does connect to the idea that we can't really go that far in thinking about how human beings might become if they lived in a completely different sort of society.

01:52:51.000 --> 01:53:08.000
I mean, you know, anthropologists have looked at whether there ever was a society based upon what Marx and Engels called primitive communism, where there was a subsistence society.

01:53:08.000 --> 01:53:21.000
It produced to use itself, not to sell and its expectations as to what was possible were formed by what was possible, given it was subsistence.

01:53:21.000 --> 01:53:33.000
So that was their expectations. Now, in a complex society, like any modern society, what people need, it partly depends upon how those needs are shaped.

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:38.000
As I've already said, but it also depends on their different circumstances.

01:53:38.000 --> 01:53:48.000
And I think in any civilized society, you wouldn't have a situation where large numbers of children go hungry.

01:53:48.000 --> 01:54:01.000
So you'd have to have a situation where families were able to access enough and therefore command enough resources to make sure that children flourish.

01:54:01.000 --> 01:54:10.000
And similarly, old people and ill people without themselves in any given moment contributing to society.

01:54:10.000 --> 01:54:19.000
So that's why people have pensions. They're no longer contributing society, but they have contributed to society in the past.

01:54:19.000 --> 01:54:28.000
So what I think you're talking about is supposing there are people who say, no, I'd just rather lie on the beach all day and not do any work to contribute to anything.

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:37.000
Now, OK, I mean, there might be such people, but I think it's very unlikely, given social norms that would prevail and so on.

01:54:37.000 --> 01:54:47.000
You might say, well, I want to, as you said yourself, you want to do these interviews and you wouldn't want anybody else to tell you who to interview and who not.

01:54:47.000 --> 01:54:51.000
Fine. Why not? I don't think my model would have any problems with that.

01:54:51.000 --> 01:55:01.000
So long as you didn't necessarily feel that you had to in order to obtain what you needed to survive in the way that you wanted to survive.

01:55:01.000 --> 01:55:09.000
You didn't feel that if you couldn't do that from your interviews, then you'd get it from somewhere else.

01:55:09.000 --> 01:55:13.000
So you'd have to that have to be a way of thinking, well, if people want to do.

01:55:13.000 --> 01:55:18.000
Well, first of all, there would be a lot more spare time so you could do it in your spare time.

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:22.000
Secondly, you wouldn't have to have anybody telling you what to do if you want to do it.

01:55:22.000 --> 01:55:27.000
You do it, you know, if you need resources. Well, you can get hold of those resources.

01:55:27.000 --> 01:55:31.000
You know about technology could get hold of computers and all the rest of it.

01:55:31.000 --> 01:55:35.000
You'd have to have the wherewithal to do that, of course.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:54.000
And but if you in your spare time were contributing to it one way or another, I mean, there used to be there still is this organization called Wages for Housework because housework is contributing to the collective well-being.

01:55:54.000 --> 01:55:59.000
It's not properly shared between typically men and women over at the moment, but never mind.

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:09.000
If it were shared, it would obviously count as socially necessary activity and all sorts of things like you're doing might well count similarly.

01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:13.000
So I don't think there's any any real problem about that.

01:56:13.000 --> 01:56:38.000
I think there would be a problem in the sense that there might be a sort of form of social disapproval if somebody chose to lie on a beach all day, but not if they were doing some creative fact that contributed in one way or another to human well-being and not just their own.

01:56:38.000 --> 01:56:54.000
So we could use the term that is sometimes used about, say, when in the UK members of the royal family, which is that they're parasites because they don't do anything useful and yet they live in luxury.

01:56:54.000 --> 01:57:07.000
Now, not everybody would agree with that because some people think they do do something useful that they, you know, they have a figurehead and the Queen is very popular and she's supposed to hold things together and so on.

01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:26.000
But what I'm trying to get at is if people are doing something, if choose to do something that is actually, let's call it parasitic on what other people do and what they depend upon is what other people produce in order for them to depend upon it.

01:57:26.000 --> 01:57:36.000
Well, you know, there may be such people, I think it's unlikely that there'd be many people who felt like that in a different form of society with a different set of values.

01:57:36.000 --> 01:57:51.000
So I think my view about about that would be there would be, on the one hand, basic services, which would everybody could have access to, and which people would be able just about to live on as a sort of not in poverty.

01:57:52.000 --> 01:58:12.000
But otherwise, if they wanted more than that, then they would probably have to have some accounting system to say, well, we are contributing something and then have to be a collective social political decision at different levels of the society about what is allowed to be counted as that and what isn't.

01:58:12.000 --> 01:58:30.000
So people who want to spend their time as artists, why not? That does contribute to human well-being. People who want to spend their time, I don't know, as I've said, just for the sake of being able to think of anything else, sort of lie on the beach all day.

01:58:30.000 --> 01:58:43.000
Well, okay, if they want to do that, fine, but they shouldn't really expect to have more, if you like, than basic necessities for living a decent life.

01:58:43.000 --> 01:59:12.000
I mean, I think these things would all have to be worked out. And it's very difficult to come to any answer other than I would expect the norm would be, I may be wrong, of course, but I would expect the norm to be that people would feel that they needed to and possibly even wanted to make a contribution to the collective well-being of society, including themselves.

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:41.000
I'm not sure, but I think there's a deep level misunderstanding going on here because I absolutely agree with this. I'm absolutely not at all on the side of those who try to sketch such a society as a problem of some people being parasitic or anything as such.

01:59:41.000 --> 02:00:09.000
I'm absolutely not on this side. I'm at the opposite side. I would argue for decoupling of very good living standards for everybody and the question of work, because I absolutely agree that most people would be prone to do stuff and to be helpful and to bring some knowledge, some skill into the reproduction of society as a whole.

02:00:09.000 --> 02:00:35.000
So I absolutely agree with that. The thing is that coming from this place of actually pushing it even further, I do think that the heavy reliance on a specific idea of self-activating and self-determining individual,

02:00:35.000 --> 02:01:03.000
that we actually would need a plurality of perspective on humans as such within this category as well. That was kind of the thing I was heading at, is that I do value people who are not active as well, because I think that they might bring in different skills.

02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:22.000
There's a value to passiveness as well, because people who are not this self-activating individual that is always self-conscious and reflective and rational, this is a very specific idea of what a human being might be.

02:01:22.000 --> 02:01:36.000
And I think there's a whole plethora of different ways of seeing oneself and acting oneself, etc. that is very, very, very much valuable as well.

02:01:36.000 --> 02:02:05.000
I'm still not sure I've completely grasped your position, because I think that in the sort of society that I have in mind, there would be plenty of space and time for people as individuals or maybe as small groups of individuals to do their own thing.

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:26.000
I think the only proviso for that would be if all they wanted to do was their own thing, and that was judged more collectively as not contributing to the collective wellbeing.

02:02:26.000 --> 02:02:39.000
They could do it, but if that's all they wanted to do and didn't want any part of what they did to contribute in whatever way to what was judged to be part of the collectivity, I think that would be a problem.

02:02:39.000 --> 02:02:45.000
And I think that that would be regarded as not playing the game, if you like.

02:02:45.000 --> 02:03:06.000
But I think the whole point about the society that I look forward to is that everybody would contribute to what was needed for human flourishing, but there would then be plenty of time left over for them to do whatever else they wanted to do.

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:18.000
But if they didn't want in any way to contribute to the collective good, then it seems to me it would be a problem and would be disapproved of, at least I would disapprove of it.

02:03:18.000 --> 02:03:25.000
I don't know whether other people would, because I think that we have a collective responsibility for one another.

02:03:25.000 --> 02:03:38.000
And therefore, I'm happy for people to do things that so long as they're not destructive in whatever spare time as if everyone wants to use the term spare time or free time.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:49.000
But on the other hand, I mean, lots of people actually love the work they do. And lots of people in our society don't love the work they do because it's not intrinsically rewarding or valuable.

02:03:49.000 --> 02:03:54.000
It might actually be socially valuable, but it's not rewarding necessarily individually.

02:03:54.000 --> 02:04:06.000
So I think I don't really think there is a problem unless you are suggesting that some people might want to be parasitic on what the other people are doing.

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:10.000
And I think I would I would think that that would meet with social disapproval.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:18.000
So long as they do contribute and then the rest of the time they do what the hell they like, which is not destructive, that's absolutely fine.

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:37.000
Indeed, that's the whole point of the society to both try to create a situation where the work that needs to be done to produce what's needed for civilized flourishing human being leading a decent life doesn't take up everybody's time.

02:04:37.000 --> 02:04:42.000
And therefore there's plenty of time left to do all sorts of other things we might be lying on the beach.

02:04:42.000 --> 02:05:01.000
Maybe a different way to maybe demonstrate what I what I mean is the question of if negotiated coordination is the mechanism with which these things are being mediated between each other.

02:05:01.000 --> 02:05:08.000
So you have the production unit, you have the coordination bodies, you have the planning committees, et cetera, et cetera.

02:05:08.000 --> 02:05:22.000
And in all of these instances, as far as I understood your model, there would be processes of negotiation involved in order to produce a collectively decided upon outcome.

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:24.000
That's how I understood it.

02:05:24.000 --> 02:05:36.000
And my point is that this is a very specific mode, a specific relay between these institutions, these layers of institutions.

02:05:36.000 --> 02:05:54.000
And this relay, this mechanism, this medium does suit specific types of persons, specific types of rationalities, specific types of qualities and qualifications better than others.

02:05:54.000 --> 02:06:08.000
So if we have people who have what in German is called Sitzfleisch, which are just like really fucking stubborn and they want their will to get through and they will like push their head through the wall and stuff like that.

02:06:08.000 --> 02:06:11.000
And they might be like overly aggressive doing so.

02:06:11.000 --> 02:06:21.000
And so they dominate the group in a very bad way in a way that is not supporting the complete group.

02:06:21.000 --> 02:06:30.000
And this is something that you will actually experience in groups that are self-organizing quite often.

02:06:30.000 --> 02:06:46.000
That there's some asshole which kind of pulls the energy of the room to himself, mostly men, and is being very dominant and is actually sorry for my French, fucking up the whole process.

02:06:46.000 --> 02:07:15.000
And the point would be that if negotiated coordination is the one relay, the one medium to transmit, to organize, to mediate, etc., then this is reducing the ways in which different qualities of people, different qualities of information, etc.

02:07:15.000 --> 02:07:17.000
can be transmitted.

02:07:17.000 --> 02:07:20.000
There's a relation between the two.

02:07:20.000 --> 02:07:30.000
If there is a homo passivus, they might really lose out within the meeting where everybody decides on how things should go along.

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:36.000
Because she or he is the homo passivus and he's not bringing forward his position.

02:07:36.000 --> 02:07:40.000
Maybe he's not reflected or he's not self-conscious or whatever.

02:07:40.000 --> 02:07:55.000
It's just the point that there's a variety of different valuable subjectivities and not all of them lie themselves naturally to a process of negotiated coordination.

02:07:55.000 --> 02:07:57.000
I guess that would be the point.

02:07:57.000 --> 02:08:00.000
I now understand what you're saying.

02:08:00.000 --> 02:08:10.000
I'm sure you obviously have and I obviously have met people like that who try to dominate things or they're just like that.

02:08:10.000 --> 02:08:14.000
They're pushing themselves forward all the time for whatever reason.

02:08:14.000 --> 02:08:17.000
So there are two things to be said about that.

02:08:17.000 --> 02:08:24.000
I have to say that one is undoubtedly that at the moment can be a problem.

02:08:24.000 --> 02:08:29.000
But if somebody is chairing a meeting, you can usually keep such people under control.

02:08:29.000 --> 02:08:33.000
Not always, but you can usually keep them under control.

02:08:33.000 --> 02:08:46.000
And interestingly enough, in my experience, it's been easier to do that face to face than online.

02:08:46.000 --> 02:08:50.000
The only way you can do it online in the end is just to cut them off.

02:08:51.000 --> 02:08:53.000
But you don't want to do that.

02:08:53.000 --> 02:08:57.000
So face to face, you just say, no, look, come on, we've got to let other people have their turn.

02:08:57.000 --> 02:08:59.000
You know, endless ways of doing it.

02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:01.000
So that's the first thing to be said.

02:09:01.000 --> 02:09:05.000
That sort of behavior can be kept under control and you can.

02:09:05.000 --> 02:09:16.000
And one of the skills of actually being a teacher is to find ways of bringing in people who tend to just sit there or be passive.

02:09:17.000 --> 02:09:22.000
In fact, one of the things you really have to do if you're a good teacher is to find a way of doing that.

02:09:22.000 --> 02:09:30.000
But the second thing is, although you get people who do behave that way at the moment,

02:09:30.000 --> 02:09:36.000
I would expect that there'd be far fewer of them in a different society.

02:09:36.000 --> 02:09:42.000
I wouldn't know how could I know whether they would disappear completely.

02:09:42.000 --> 02:09:51.000
But given the fact on the one hand that I think they can be kept under control by somebody who's chairing the meeting.

02:09:51.000 --> 02:09:54.000
And on the other hand, I think there'd be far fewer of them.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:10:02.000
I can't see that that's going to be a big problem that they would behave in such a way as to prevent the tacit knowledge of other people

02:10:02.000 --> 02:10:07.000
or the passive knowledge of other people from coming forth or being drawn forth.

02:10:08.000 --> 02:10:11.000
So I can see the point you're making.

02:10:11.000 --> 02:10:18.000
And it obviously is a point that, as I say, we've all experienced people like that.

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:21.000
But I don't see it as being insuperable.

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:36.000
Yeah, I guess I would still stick to the point that I would only stick to the point that I would argue for a plurality of methods as well.

02:10:36.000 --> 02:10:42.000
I mean, the idea of negotiated coordination, I do understand absolutely.

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:47.000
And I do think this is a very, very valuable and essential part of the whole thing.

02:10:47.000 --> 02:11:03.000
I just do think that we need like 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 different other methods that accompany negotiated coordination in order to make things work at the end.

02:11:03.000 --> 02:11:06.000
And I guess that's your point as well.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:09.000
Give us an example of what one of these other methods might be.

02:11:09.000 --> 02:11:14.000
I mean, one of them, and this has nothing to do with tacit knowledge, I guess.

02:11:14.000 --> 02:11:21.000
One of them would be the use of modern information and communication technology.

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:24.000
But it's not only that. It's not only that.

02:11:24.000 --> 02:11:40.000
It's also that if someone does have an intuition, so to speak, in terms of something that might well be useful for some kind of purpose,

02:11:40.000 --> 02:11:50.000
but this person is not very good in talking, not very good in communicating with other humans,

02:11:50.000 --> 02:11:58.000
is like in general very much not suited for negotiated coordination as a person.

02:11:58.000 --> 02:12:11.000
You know, they do not, the way that they are set up does not lend itself nicely to this mode of coordinating things like negotiated coordination.

02:12:11.000 --> 02:12:25.000
Then I would say it might very well be that this person could bring rich things or ideas or whatever it might be at the end into the world,

02:12:25.000 --> 02:12:32.000
even though he or she might not be suited for this mechanism of negotiated coordination.

02:12:32.000 --> 02:12:42.000
And then the question would be, how would this person acquire, for example, the resources to bring into the world

02:12:42.000 --> 02:12:49.000
whatever he or she might want to produce if this road is not hers or his?

02:12:49.000 --> 02:12:56.000
No, I can see that. I was going to say that if somebody has an intuition,

02:12:56.000 --> 02:13:02.000
there's no reason in the way I see the world, I envisage things.

02:13:02.000 --> 02:13:05.000
There's no reason why they shouldn't follow that intuition.

02:13:05.000 --> 02:13:15.000
The only way in which the problems that you're raising might arise is if in order to follow them, they need to do so collectively.

02:13:15.000 --> 02:13:24.000
And that's to say they need to involve other people and they can't convince other people that their intuition is worth following.

02:13:24.000 --> 02:13:30.000
Well, I can see that that could be a problem. But I mean, I don't really think that that's insuperable.

02:13:30.000 --> 02:13:41.000
I mean, in subsequent discussions and things that Fikret and I have written, I mean, one of the things that we've thought of is that you could have

02:13:41.000 --> 02:13:52.000
and other people have come up with similar ideas, you could have, for example, a body like a research council that people could apply to

02:13:52.000 --> 02:13:58.000
and say, look, I've got this idea and I don't know whether it will work or not, but I need some resources.

02:13:58.000 --> 02:14:09.000
So just like when you apply for a research grant, but if you want to have access to collective resources,

02:14:09.000 --> 02:14:22.000
then there's got to be some way of the collective reaching a view on whether that's a worthwhile use of those resources.

02:14:22.000 --> 02:14:34.000
Now, some people in dealing with this issue have suggested that everybody should have a certain allowance of resources, if you like,

02:14:34.000 --> 02:14:44.000
that they could use in whatever way they like or make available for anybody else to use on their behalf.

02:14:44.000 --> 02:14:52.000
That's one way of thinking about it. So there are a number of ways in which you can think about how do people get access to resources

02:14:52.000 --> 02:15:00.000
if they can't really convince anybody that they should be able to use collective resources for that purpose.

02:15:00.000 --> 02:15:04.000
And maybe there isn't such a maybe there is no way of doing that.

02:15:04.000 --> 02:15:08.000
I mean, it would that would be a form of total autarky.

02:15:08.000 --> 02:15:22.000
You could use social resources just because you wanted to, which would be fine if you could manage to devise a system,

02:15:22.000 --> 02:15:32.000
which could include, of course, convincing other people that even though the outcome of your intuition is unpredictable, it's worth following.

02:15:32.000 --> 02:15:39.000
So I think you may be you may be worrying about an issue which can't be solved.

02:15:39.000 --> 02:15:42.000
But that may not be true. I don't know.

02:15:42.000 --> 02:15:51.000
There are people who have, as I said, tried to devise ways of making resources available to do even if you can't convince anybody else,

02:15:51.000 --> 02:15:59.000
like the fact that everybody would have an allowance that they could give to themselves or convey to other people.

02:15:59.000 --> 02:16:04.000
Yeah. And I guess it's a problem that is not like unique to your model.

02:16:04.000 --> 02:16:13.000
So it's it will come up in general if we want to decide about how to spend the resources.

02:16:13.000 --> 02:16:21.000
Yeah. OK. So how should we approach it if we would want to bring into existence negotiated coordination?

02:16:21.000 --> 02:16:27.000
What would be the experiments, the next steps like how would a transformation go about?

02:16:27.000 --> 02:16:29.000
How should we approach it?

