02:16:40.000 --> 02:16:50.000
What is the political process through which we have to go in order to go beyond capitalism?

02:16:50.000 --> 02:16:56.000
Because you couldn't have negotiated coordination of the sort that I have in mind within capitalism.

02:16:56.000 --> 02:17:01.000
So how do we get beyond capitalism?

02:17:01.000 --> 02:17:07.000
I don't know if you've come across the work of this woman in America called Jody Dean.

02:17:07.000 --> 02:17:13.000
Her three most interesting, well, three that I've been most interested in books.

02:17:13.000 --> 02:17:19.000
First of all, the one she called Communist Horizon, the Communist Horizon.

02:17:19.000 --> 02:17:34.000
And what she means by that is the horizon is a metaphor because horizons are a distinction between what you can see and what you can't see beyond.

02:17:34.000 --> 02:17:43.000
And the communist horizon is seen beyond what you can't see to what you she would like to see, which is communism.

02:17:43.000 --> 02:17:57.000
And that term distinguishes the communist view because it's a sharp discontinuity between what we've got and what we would like to move towards from social

02:17:57.000 --> 02:18:11.000
democracy or all these improvements within capitalism, the commons and horizontalism and crack capitalism and all these things that are around.

02:18:11.000 --> 02:18:18.000
So that's the first thing. And the second one is her book called Crowds and Parties.

02:18:18.000 --> 02:18:35.000
Crowds are what happens when you get these manifestations like the Occupy movement in New York or mass demonstrations against a nuclear power station or a new oil field or whatever.

02:18:35.000 --> 02:18:46.000
And they come and go and they're crowds and they have a power and they carry people with them, people involved in them think, great, this is the future.

02:18:46.000 --> 02:18:50.000
But of course, it never is because it comes and then it goes.

02:18:50.000 --> 02:19:02.000
So what she what she argues is what you need is a party that has a continuity, learns, has a history and so on.

02:19:02.000 --> 02:19:09.000
And the her third book is what the Americans called called Comrades.

02:19:09.000 --> 02:19:12.000
We call them comrades, but never mind.

02:19:12.000 --> 02:19:28.000
And and there she's she's trying to draw a distinction between friends who you can disagree with, but are still friends, family, likewise, neighbors, and so on.

02:19:28.000 --> 02:19:37.000
Again, allies, but comrades are people who share the same values and vision that you have.

02:19:37.000 --> 02:19:47.000
And she gets this, of course, from her study of parties and comrades then are people who you don't have to be friends with, you don't have to like.

02:19:47.000 --> 02:19:55.000
But if you're committed to the same project, then you enter into a sort of sense of mutual obligation.

02:19:55.000 --> 02:20:00.000
Your comrades, you expect something from other comrades and they expect something from you.

02:20:00.000 --> 02:20:07.000
So this is just a rather convoluted way of saying a political process of how you get there.

02:20:07.000 --> 02:20:19.000
And here we move on to a different field altogether, which is my current sort of vision of the political process is basically a Gramscian approach.

02:20:20.000 --> 02:20:26.000
Because Gramsci has this idea that there will always be crises.

02:20:26.000 --> 02:20:38.000
There are small scale crises, but then there are what he calls an organic crisis, which is where the ruling class can no longer continue to rule in the same way that they have been ruling in the past.

02:20:38.000 --> 02:20:43.000
They don't only rule in the developed capitalist countries by force.

02:20:43.000 --> 02:20:51.000
They also rule by consent through hegemony and so on of ruling class ideas.

02:20:51.000 --> 02:20:57.000
And when it comes to an organic crisis, then there's a war of what he calls maneuver.

02:20:57.000 --> 02:21:01.000
There's a war of how the crisis is going to be resolved.

02:21:01.000 --> 02:21:30.000
And his argument is that the outcome of that war depends upon the previous war of position, which is a long process, probably of decades, in which there is a movement to try and create on the one hand a counter hegemony, an alternative way of trying to link everything together from the ruling class.

02:21:30.000 --> 02:21:56.000
But on the other hand, equally importantly, if not more importantly, there is the creation of in various sort of cooperative, associative, prefigurative ways, institutions of one sort or another, which can then be drawn upon when it comes to the war of maneuver.

02:21:56.000 --> 02:22:15.000
And he got this idea. He developed this idea. You probably know all about this, but he developed this idea when he was thinking about why was it that the Russian Revolution succeeded, but the Hungarian Revolution, the German Revolution, the other European revolutions didn't succeed.

02:22:15.000 --> 02:22:41.000
And his analysis was that in Russia, with a relatively underdeveloped civil society, all the Bolsheviks needed to do was to see state power, which they managed to do, and then set about, if you like, creating the socialist consciousness, which was needed to build a different form of society.

02:22:41.000 --> 02:22:56.000
Whereas in Germany, in particular, there was a well-developed civil society in which ruling class ideas held sway, even though they were not part of the state.

02:22:56.000 --> 02:23:11.000
And so although the revolutions looked at if they might succeed, and of course, in the Soviet Union, they hoped they would succeed because they didn't think they could build socialism alone in one country, but they didn't succeed.

02:23:11.000 --> 02:23:28.000
And Grouchy's view was that was because the war of position, preparations building up to the revolution hadn't happened to the same extent because of the strength of civil society, which was imbued by ruling class ideas.

02:23:28.000 --> 02:23:40.000
So that's where this, I think that's where his view of the war of position. So that's how I see things at the moment. I mean, you can't automatically apply something that was developed.

02:23:40.000 --> 02:23:51.000
Well, probably 90 years ago, or the rudiments of it to today, but nevertheless, it's a very interesting way, I think, of thinking about things.

02:23:51.000 --> 02:24:08.000
So that, I think, is what I would look to if I was thinking of, well, how can we move towards a post-capitalist society where negotiated coordination and social ownership has a chance of working?

